    <name>
      <text>Indicating the argument used in the proof</text>
    </name>
    <questiontext format="html">
      <text><![CDATA[<p>Consider the statement below and the proof given.
<br>Fill in the blanks to indicate which argument is used in each step of the proof.</p>

<p><b>Statement</b></p>
<p>Suppose that \(A\) is a square matrix. Let \(B\) be the square matrix obtained from \(A\) by multiplying a single row by the scalar \(\alpha\), or by multiplying a single column by a scalar \(\alpha\). 
<br>Then, \(\text{det}(B) = \alpha \text{det}(A)\)</p>

<p><b>Proof</b></p>
<p>Let \(i\) be the index of the row of \(A\) which was multiplied by \(\alpha\) to obtain \(B\). Then, </p>
<table>
  <tr height="100px">
    <td width="400px">\(\text{det}(B) = \sum_{j=1}^{n}(-1)^{i+j} [B]_{ij} \text{det}(B(i|j)) \)</td>
    <td width="400px">by [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]]<br>[[feedback:prt1]]</td>
  </tr>
  <tr height="100px">
    <td>\(\hspace{56px}= \sum_{j=1}^{n}(-1)^{i+j} [B]_{ij} \text{det}(A(i|j))\)</td>
    <td>using \(B(i|j)=A(i|j)\) because <br>[[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]]<br>[[feedback:prt2]]</td>
  </tr>
  <tr height="100px">
    <td>\(\hspace{56px}= \sum_{j=1}^{n}(-1)^{i+j} \alpha [A]_{ij} \text{det}(A(i|j))\)</td>
    <td>using \([B]_{ij}=\alpha [A]_{ij}\) because <br>[[input:ans3]] [[validation:ans3]]<br>[[feedback:prt3]]</td>
  </tr>
  <tr height="100px">
    <td>\(\hspace{56px}= \alpha \sum_{j=1}^{n}(-1)^{i+j} [A]_{ij} \text{det}(A(i|j))\)</td>
    <td>by [[input:ans4]] [[validation:ans4]]<br>[[feedback:prt4]]</td>
  </tr>
  <tr height="100px">
    <td>\(\hspace{56px}= \alpha \text{det}(A)\)</td>
    <td>by [[input:ans5]] [[validation:ans5]]<br>[[feedback:prt5]]</td>
  </tr>
</table>

<p>The proof for the case of a multiple of a column is entirely similar.</p>]]></text>
    </questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="html">
      <text><![CDATA[<h3>Worked Solution</h3>

<p><b>Proof</b></p>
<table>
  <tr height="50px">
    <td width="380px">\(\text{det}(B) = \sum_{j=1}^{n}(-1)^{i+j} [B]_{ij} \text{det}(B(i|j)) \)</td>
    <td width="700px">by <b>the definition of the determinant</b>.</td>
  </tr>
  <tr height="50px">
    <td>\(\hspace{56px}= \sum_{j=1}^{n}(-1)^{i+j} [B]_{ij} \text{det}(A(i|j))\)</td>
    <td>using \(B(i|j)=A(i|j)\) because <b>all rows except row \(i\) are the same for \(A\) and \(B\)</b>.</td>
  </tr>
  <tr height="50px">
    <td>\(\hspace{56px}= \sum_{j=1}^{n}(-1)^{i+j} \alpha [A]_{ij} \text{det}(A(i|j))\)</td>
    <td>using \([B]_{ij}=\alpha [A]_{ij}\) because <b>\(B\) was obtained by multiplying row \(i\) of \(A\) by \(\alpha\)</b>.</td>
  </tr>
  <tr height="50px">
    <td>\(\hspace{56px}= \alpha \sum_{j=1}^{n}(-1)^{i+j} [A]_{ij} \text{det}(A(i|j))\)</td>
    <td>by <b>distributivity</b>.</td>
  </tr>
  <tr height="50px">
    <td>\(\hspace{56px}= \alpha \text{det}(A)\)</td>
    <td>by <b>the definition of the determinant</b>.</td>
  </tr>
</table>

<p>The proof for the case of a multiple of a column is entirely similar.</p>]]></text>
